sec.p:
MRF is a magnetic field-assisted precision finishing process developed [
1
] and commercialized by QED Technologies, Inc. [
2
]. MRF has revolutionized the way optics is being made and it has gained broad acceptance by most of the world’s leading optics industries. MRF has been used for finishing a large variety of brittle materials ranging from optical glasses to hard crystals [
3
]. This process utilizes magnetorheological polishing (MRP) fluid to polish different kinds of materials. MRP fluid consists of magnetic carbonyl iron particles (CIPs) and non-magnetic abrasive particles (NMAPs), water or other carrier liquid, and surfactant. The MRP fluid forms a conformal polishing tool and therefore it can polish a variety of shapes, including flat, convex, and concave. With an appropriate combination of MRP fluid and other finishing parameters, it has successfully polished a variety of materials to sub-nanometer surface roughness value.

Shorey et al. [
4
] designed and tested a magnetorheometer for studying yield stress and viscosity of MRP fluids. The yield stress is found as a function of CIPs concentration and magnetic field intensity. Huang et al. [
5
] developed a theoretical model for yield stress to analyse the effect of magnetic field on the MR fluid having no NMAPs. However, the study of the effect of other parameters, such as size and concentration of NMAPs, size of CIPs, and temperature of MRP fluid, is necessary from MRF process point of view.

The experimental investigations in MRF process include design and fabrication of different types of setups as per the workpiece requirements, study of effect of process parameters on the responses, synthesis of effective MR fluid in terms of MRR, surface finish, etc. Tani and Kawata [
9
] developed a polishing method and named as ‘Magnetic float polishing’. The magnetic fluid consists of a ferro-colloid magnetite (Fe3O4) and silicon carbide as NMAPs in the carrier liquid (eicosyl naphthalene). The theory of magnetic levitation of NMAPs is described and it is concluded that the finishing is performed by the scratching mechanism rather than the rolling one. Kurobe and Imanaka [
10
] developed a polishing method which uses electromagnet for energizing magnetic fluid. It is found that the pulse magnetic field has higher material removal than the static one. It is also reported that the small size NMAPs give higher material removal rate (MRR) and finishing rate (FR) (nm/s) compared to bigger size NMAPs. Suzuki et al. [
11
] demonstrated a method for finishing curved workpiece (single-crystal LiNbO3) by magnetic field-assisted finishing process. When colloidal silica is used as NMAPs, surface roughness of 10 nm, R
max, has been obtained. Forming of MRP fluid into a ribbon and maintaining fluid properties (e.g. apparent viscosity, temperature, and homogeneity) are the most critical factors in MRF process [
12
].

Jacobs et al. [
13
] reported the removal of asymmetric figure errors during MRF. Surface roughness of ∼1 nm has been achieved with FR between 16.67 and 166.67 nm/s, which seems to be quite high. A method of sedimentation measurement is demonstrated by Kordonski and Golini [
14
], which is one of the prime concerns of MR fluid stability. It is shown that the specially developed methods of the slurry handling, pumping, and online monitoring and maintaining the MR fluid properties provide stability to the MRP fluid. Shorey et al. [
15
] found that the nano-hardness of CIPs is important in MRF with non-aqueous MR fluids without using NMAPs, but it is relatively unimportant when aqueous MR fluids with NMAPs are used. MRR increases with the addition of NMAPs such as CeO2, Al2O3, and diamond. The diamond particles are ten times more efficient than CeO2 and Al2O3 particles. Kordonski and Golini [
16
] designed a few auxiliary devices which are necessary for proper circulation of MR fluid in the MRF process. It regulates the MR fluid flowrate by feedback-assisted computer control so that the MRP fluid can be continuously circulated. A 3D silicon micro-channel structure was finished by MRF process [
17
]. The roughness of bottom and side surfaces of the silicon channel was reduced by a factor of 5–10. The pressure drop of a gas flow through this silicon micro-channel was lowered to 26.7 per cent of the pressure drop in an unfinished micro-channel. It was also found that the concentration of magnetic particles and strength of the magnetic field are important parameters for MRF process. The NMAPs move away from the magnet (towards workpiece surface) due to the magnetic levitation force. The magnetic levitation force (F
ml) [
18
] is given by
(1)where Va
 is the volume of non-magnetic body (or NMAPs), M the intensity of magnetization of magnetic fluid, μ0 the permeability of free space, and ∇H the gradient of magnetic field.

The MRF process is used for fabrication of curved surfaces on silicon-based micro-structures [
19
]. The edge effect is found to be very important when the target workpiece gets smaller because of much higher magnetic field intensity at the edges. However, the undesirable edge effect can be profitably used for the fabrication of curved surface structures on millimetre scale (2–3 mm). The results could have been better if CeO2 had been used as an abrasive constituent of MRP fluid in the place of MR fluid (without any NMAPs).

It is possible to polish soft optical polymers like PMMA, CVD polycrystalline ZnS, and water-soluble single-crystal KDP by appropriately choosing the composition of MRP fluid [
20
]. The systematic alteration of MR fluid chemistry (specifically, slurry pH) is required to match the unique physical properties of individual workpiece material. Jung et al. [
21
] focused on increasing MRR using sintered iron–carbon nano-tubes compound as abrasive in the MR fluid. It increases FR in the case of Al2O3–TiC hard disc slider. In this finishing process, a rectilinear alternating motion of the workpiece is superimposed with the rotating motion of the permanent magnet tool. The main limitation of this process is that the rotational speed of the tool cannot be increased beyond a certain critical r/min due to the spilling out of the polishing medium from the tool which reduces MRR as well as change in surface roughness value (ΔR
a). This seems to be good for finishing external surfaces of the workpieces but not so good for the complex internal geometries.

Cheng et al. [
22
] designed a MR fluid-based two-axes wheel finishing tool which rotates about its own axis and at the same time about the co-rotating axis. The surface roughness of parabolic K9 lens of 60 mm diameter is reduced from 3.8 to 1.2 nm after 10 min, and the shape accuracy with an initial value of 2.27 to 0.36 mm rms after 60 more minutes of fine polishing. A penalized multi-response Taguchi method has been developed [
23
] to show that the optimization procedure can simultaneously maximize MRR and minimize surface roughness without violating the boundary constraints. When maximizing, the MRR is given higher weightage over minimizing the surface roughness value.

For any finishing process, type, magnitude, and direction of forces acting on the workpiece play a major role on the quality of the finished surface. It has been observed [
15
] from the atomic force microscope images that NMAPs move towards the workpiece surface because of low magnetic field gradient. This movement of NMAPs towards the workpiece increases MRR. A transition from a two-body to a three-body abrasion model for material removal is also hypothesized. The difference between the normal force acting on the workpiece surface in MRF process and conventional polishing process has been discussed in Shorey et al. [
24
]. The normal force on the workpiece in the conventional polishing process transferred from the polishing polyurethane pad is of the order of millinewton in magnitude [
25
], and it sometimes results in deep scratches on the workpiece surface. In the MRF process, NMAPs create relatively low normal load on the workpiece surface and it is estimated to be several times less than that of conventional polishing [
26
]. This normal force can be estimated by the sum of the magnetic buoyant force and the component of the hydrostatic force normal to the workpiece surface.

A two-dimensional (2D) force sensor for simultaneous measurement of both drag and normal forces in MRF process has been used [
27
]. The mechanism governing MRR in the MRF process for optical glasses, in terms of the hydrodynamic pressure and shear stress in the converging gap is addressed. This study demonstrates that the volumetric MRR increases with an increase in shear stress. The shear stress exhibits a positive linear dependence on a material figure of merit (FOM) that depends on Young’s modulus, fracture toughness, and hardness of the workpiece. However, the effect of process parameters, such as concentration of magnetic particles and NMAPs, wheel speed, and working gap, have not been studied with respect to shear stress in MRF process.

It is found by Miao et al. [
28
] that normal and tangential forces increase initially with the addition of nano-diamond particles but they stabilize at higher concentration. Significant increase in tangential and normal forces is observed by decreasing the working gap. It is also found that normal force increases with an increase in wheel speed but it has no apparent effect on tangential force. It may happen when the shear strength of the MR fluid is lower than the tangential force acting on the solid constituents (CIPs and NMAPs). As a result, the MRP fluid itself gets sheared by the solid constituents instead of holding them and building up (or increasing) the shear force acting on the workpiece.

DeGroote et al. [
26
] introduced a new MRR model for MRF of glass. Validation of the proposed MRR model for MRF of glass is done with the experimental data [
26
]. These experiments were conducted using nano-diamond added MRP fluid and a set of six optical glasses as workpieces. The MRR increases with the increase in nano-diamond powder concentration and it gives a maxima. Glasses with phosphate network formers require less drag force to remove material compared to glasses with silicon network formers. It is observed that in MRF, MRR is best described, not only by one single term, covering glass mechanical properties, but also with a combination of terms that involve mechanics, polishing particle properties, and chemistry.

MRF is successfully used as a finishing process in industrial applications such as finishing of normal and free-form optics, light weight optics, extreme ultraviolet lithography applications, phase plate applications, high laser fluence application, transmitted wave-front applications, and diamond turned surfaces [
33
]. Jacobs et al. [
34
] reported the finishing results for LiF, ZnSe, CaF2, AMTIR-l, ZnS, MgF2 sapphire, and CVD diamond. MRF of optical glasses is accomplished with MRP fluid containing CeO2 to accelerate material removal process. The infrared materials can be finished by substituting nano-alumina or nano-diamond abrasives by CeO2 and using optimized MRF process parameters. Application of MRF process for removal of asymmetric grinding errors and diamond turning marks has been demonstrated [
35
]. Some examples of batch finishing of glass aspheres are also reported. The MRF process is also used for finishing micro-parts such as micro-nozzle. Figure 8(a) shows the micro-nozzle which is fabricated by electro-chemical micro-machining (ECMM) process. Figure 8(b) and (c) show different sections and surface roughness plots of micro-nozzle before and after MRF, respectively [
36
]. It is clear that surface roughness is reduced in all the sections of micro-nozzle after MRF.
Fig. 8
(a) Micro-nozzle fabricated by ECMM. Surface roughness plots and different sections of micro-nozzle (b) before and (c) after, finishing by MRF process

The orbital AFF process is normally used to finish blind and shallow cavities such as coins and dies. It is the combination of form grinding and two-way AFF process. Here, medium reciprocates in two ways and the orbital motion is given to the form tool (Fig. 10(b)) [
43
].

Two-way AFF process (Fig. 9) extrudes the medium along to and fro directions. It is normally used to finish cylindrical (internal and external) surfaces and complex-shaped surfaces which have through holes. The μ-AFF process is similar to the two-way except that it uses low viscosity medium and very fine APs. This helps the medium to flow through micro-size features (50–750 μm). The μ-AFF ideally suits to various manufacturing sectors such as automotive, medical, and extrusion dies. [
44
].

Singh and Shan [
45
] used the medium made of silicon polymer base carrier, hydrocarbon gel, and magnetic APs in magnetic AFF process. Magnetic field is applied around the workpiece in AFF and observed that the field significantly affects the material removal and Δ Ra. This would work well only for low viscosity medium in which the migration of magnetic APs towards the magnets (or workpiece) is possible.

Electrochemical-aided abrasive flow machining [
46
] uses polymeric electrolytes such as gelated polymers and water-gels as the base carrier. The ion conductivity of electrolytes is much lower than the conductivity of electrolytes employed in ordinary electrochemical machining. It further decreases by the addition of inorganic fillers (APs). This polymeric electrolyte medium in semi-liquid paste is forced through small interelectrode gap. Experimental investigations revealed that this hybrid process offers technological and economical advantages compared to AFF alone.

Spiral fluted screw is placed at the centre of the hole in the workpiece as an obstruction and is rotated using external energy source. The rotational motion of the screw lifts the medium from lower region to upper region, and tries to finish the hole while passing through it [
47
]. This process might show good results for high viscous medium only if it can properly adhere to the screw. In the case of low viscosity medium, there is a possibility of slip between the medium and the screw. Some researchers have used drill bit [
48
] in the place of screw to achieve almost similar objective, and called it as drill bit-guided AFF.

Depth of indentation depends on Fr, while Fa and Ft Ft(Fc=Fa2+Ft2
 
 ) are responsible to remove the material in the form of μ-chips. Thus, the finishing force (Ff=Fr2+Fa2+Ft2
 
 ) is a vector sum of all the three forces involved in the finishing action. Hence, as the rotational speed increases, FR and ΔR
a increase.

A mathematical simulation model was presented [
53
] to determine the characteristics of the medium flow during finishing using constitutive equations of Maxwell considering it as non-Newtonian fluid. Maxwell model takes care of only the elastic component whereas the Kelvin Viogt model takes care of viscous component of the medium. Since the medium is visco-elastic, combined model of Maxwell–Kelvin Viogt or Standard Linear solid model should have more accurately taken care of flow characteristics of the medium.

A finite element approach was proposed [
54
–
57
] for the prediction of stresses developed during finishing of cylindrical passage by AFF process. Here, it is assumed that the medium exhibits linear viscous flow property. Its properties are independent of temperature and constant with regards to time and space. Theoretical models for micro-ploughing and micro-cutting are also proposed. In the case of aggressive (high-viscosity medium with high forces) finishing, the medium exhibits non-linear viscous flow properties and its viscosity decreases with an increase in temperature. If the non-linearity and temperature effects are considered, one can enhance the model accuracy and it would give a better agreement with the experimental results. Gorana et al. [
58
–
60
] developed a theoretical model of forces acting on a single AP for studying the finishing mechanism of AFF process. Comparison of theoretical model results with the experimental data of force and active APs density obtained during AFF process has been reported [
59
]. AFF process is modelled using finite element method for finishing of external surfaces and to find forces acting on a single AP by assuming the medium as visco-plastic material [
61
]. The model results could be more accurate if the medium was considered as visco-elastic material.

Fletcher et al. [
62
] found that shear rate increases when the medium passes through the restricted passage; hence, shear stress acting on the workpiece also increases. It is also concluded that greater finishing action is achieved as a result of longer piston stroke duration, due to higher wall shear stress generated. The wall shear stress depends on extrusion pressure, passage cross-sectional area, and medium viscosity. It seems that the greater finishing action in longer piston stroke duration is achieved due to the finishing actions by both more number of APs per unit stroke and higher wall shear stress due to restricted passage.

Petri et al. [
63
] adopted neural network modelling technique for developing a comprehensive model for AFF. Lam and Smith [
64
] applied cascade-correlation neural network modelling to the case of finishing of automotive engine air intake manifold. This neural network modelling is used to predict the instant at which the finishing process should be terminated to meet the airflow specifications. Jain and Jain [
65
] proposed a generalized backpropagation neural network model and a second network which parallelizes the augmented Lagrange multiplier algorithm. Sarah et al. [
66
] presented a neural network model as an offline controller for AFF of automotive engine manifold.

For online monitoring of material removal and surface roughness in AFF process, acoustic emission (AE) technique has been applied [
67
] and found that the AE signal is highly dependent on the initial surface roughness of the workpiece. The AERMS of the signal is sensitive to extrusion pressure and other AFF process parameters, which affect material removal. Data-dependent system technique is used to analyse the AE signals acquired during AFF process. It has also been found that aluminium workpiece gives stronger signals than steel, because of higher material removal from aluminium workpiece compared to steel.

Jain and Jain [
68
] presented a simple model for heat transfer in AFF considering heat flow to the workpiece and medium using one-dimensional (1D) unsteady state heat transfer theory. However, it has been concluded that the rise in temperature is small in AFF. A 2D/3D unsteady state heat transfer analysis would give more accurate results.

Fletcher et al. [
62
] experimentally determined thermal properties of the medium such as thermal conductivity, specific heat capacity and surface heat transfer coefficient of medium for the various mixtures of polyborosiloxane and silicon carbide abrasive. These experimental results were compared with mathematical model, which were then used to study thermal behaviour of medium as a function of its composition and temperature. Specific heat capacity of the mixture was modelled based on the mass proportion of each constituent. Surface heat transfer coefficient between interface of mixture and die was predominantly found as a function of APs concentration. Type of polymer and APs size were found to be less significant for surface heat transfer coefficient.

In view of the above-mentioned limitations of AFF and MRF processes, a hybrid finishing process was thought by combining these two processes, leading to the development of MRAFF process [
69
]. The MRAFF process maintains the versatility of AFF process and at the same time introduces determinism and in-process controllability of the rheological properties of the polishing medium of MRF process.

Jha and Jain [
69
] concluded that magnetic flux density is the main contributor in improving surface finish among the three main variables: magnetic flux density, extrusion pressure, and finishing cycles. As the magnetic flux density increases by increasing magnetizing current to electromagnet, CIP chains hold the NMAPs more firmly and thereby result in faster finishing action. Another important finding from the analysis of experimental results at different finishing cycles is that the actual finishing takes place only after removal of all the loosely held ploughed material left out after grinding. The surface roughness value progressively decreases with further increase in finishing cycles till the critical surface finish is achieved. It depends on the NMAPs size and extrusion pressure [
70
].

MRAFF is capable of super finishing hard materials such as silicon nitride (Si3N4) using boron carbide, silicon carbide, and diamond abrasives [
71
]. Silicon carbide is found to be more effective in finishing Si3N4 workpiece in comparison with boron carbide. Experimental study on stainless steel workpieces and theoretical modelling of finishing forces reveal that the relative size ratio of CIPs and NMAPs plays an important role in finishing performance [
72
]. The value of ΔR
a decreases as the size of CIPs becomes smaller because of decrease in the interparticle magnetic force between CIPs which governs the force responsible for holding NMAPs during shearing action and restraining CIPs chains from breaking. This phenomenon is further investigated by the rheological study of MRP medium [
73
]. It is found that shear thinning nature of the MRP fluids is due to the fast rupturing of CIP chains at high shear rates.

However, the disadvantages of MRAFF process include low FR (nm/cycle), particularly on hard materials. The FR for stainless steel workpiece (hardness 358 BHN) is 0.65 nm/cycle and it is 0.09 nm/cycle [
71
] in the case of silicon-nitride as harder workpiece material (hardness 2718 BHN). The experiments were conducted at a pressure of 37.5 bar and a magnetic field of 0.6  T in both the cases. One of the possible reasons for low FR in MRAFF process is that the interaction between the NMAPs and the work surface is in straight line sweeping a small area. Second, only a small percentage of NMAPs which are on the periphery of the slug actually participate in the finishing operation. To reduce the time of finishing, there is a need for more interaction between an individual NMAP and workpiece over a longer length in a single stroke covering a larger area of workpiece. Also, in MRAFF process, magnetic field is applied to the cylindrical fixture with two core materials of an electromagnet which are placed opposite to each other [
69
]. Due to this, magnetic field in front of the core material is high and it becomes very low on either side of the core material. Least magnetic field is observed on the cylindrical fixture at a point which is perpendicular to the line joining these two core materials of the electromagnet. Hence, workpiece kept in this zone of low magnetic field is, comparatively, less finished than the one kept in the zone in front of the core material. Researchers are working to achieve uniform nano-level finishing on different types of complex objects with or without the application of magnetic field.

Sato et al. [
74
] developed a magnetic field-assisted internal finishing technique for copper tubes using MR fluid-based slurry mixed with diamond abrasives. The copper tube held in a chuck is rotated by a motor and is simultaneously vibrated in the axial direction with a crank mechanism. Use of lower exciting current produced a smoother finished surface with less intermittent cutting marks, because of shallower depth of cut under lower magnetic field condition.

Simjian [
75
] developed a polishing device for polishing irregular objects employing a mixture of abrasives such as carborundum, a magnetic powder as iron filings, and a liquid as lubricating oil. This mixture is housed in a non-magnetic container in which the workpiece is placed. The current to the electromagnet coils is switched on in such a way that it generates a rotating magnetic field. However, this patent does not mention any finishing results obtained from the proposed device.

Sadiq and Shunmugam [
76
] developed a finishing process similar to the conventional honing to polish external curved surfaces using MRP medium. The workpiece is rotated within the medium and at the same time a reciprocating motion is provided to the medium. The major disadvantage of this process is that the electromagnet core and the workpiece surface are separated by a thick wall of the polishing medium container. Due to this, there is a major reduction in the magnetic field intensity and hence low finishing forces act during the finishing process resulting in low FR. For stainless steel workpiece, the final surface roughness value achieved was in the range 1.3–1.7 μm. Also, this configuration of the setup is unable to polish internal surface of the workpiece. Finite element analysis was also performed [
77
] to understand the nature of magnetic field likely to be produced to calculate the axial stress due to the flow of MR fluid, and to predict final surface roughness value (R
a). The comparison of results reveals just satisfactory agreement. However, this analysis did not consider radial stresses developed in the medium. A detailed computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulation of the polishing medium is essential for in-depth understanding of the process.

Jha and Jain [
72
] developed a surface roughness simulation model for MRAFF process. Das et al. [
78
] did 1D CFD simulation of MRP medium using finite difference method to evaluate the axial stress developed during the process. However, in both these cases, radial stress due to the flow of polishing medium has not been considered to calculate normal indentation force on the workpiece through NMAPs. Also, the finishing forces are computed by considering the polishing medium in static state without accounting for the shearing action of the fluid during polishing.

To enhance the process performance, NMAPs percentage in the medium can be increased or a method can be devised to increase NMAPs–workpiece interaction or both. To maintain the rheological properties of MR fluid, the NMAPs concentration cannot be increased beyond a limit. Also, there is a need to generate uniform magnetic field in the finishing zone to get uniform finishing around the workpiece surface. There are two ways to increase NMAPs–workpiece interaction. One way is to rotate the medium itself and the other is to rotate the workpiece. Rotation of workpiece is difficult in the existing MRAFF setup with the possible chances of leakage of the medium as its base material consists of mineral oil also. Therefore, rotation of the medium has been adapted by rotating the magnetic field and the process is named as rotational-MRAFF (R-MRAFF) process [
79
].

In R-MRAFF process, due to the helical motion, the length traversed by an active NMAP is more as compared to the length traversed in MRAFF process for the same number of finishing cycles and it increases with the rotational speed of the magnet. Therefore, NMAPs cut more number of peaks in one cycle in R-MRAFF process compared to MRAFF. Hence, better finishing performance (higher FR and lower final R
a value) is achieved in R-MRAFF process than MRAFF under the similar experimental conditions. R-MRAFF process is capable of producing mirror-like finished surface in the nanometre range and surface roughness as low as 110 nm on flat stainless steel, 50 nm on flat brass workpiece [
82
], and 16 nm on cylindrical stainless steel workpiece [
79
] are achieved.

R-MRAFF process uses permanent magnets; hence, the magnetic field in the finishing zone cannot be varied [
79
] like the electromagnet. For finishing materials with different hardnesses, permanent magnets with different strengths are to be used which reduces the productivity of the process. Online monitoring of the roughness parameters can be implemented in R-MRAFF process which will give better automation in the process.
